  "course_description": "Topics vary. Each colloquium treats a different theme in depth, often combining reading and seminar discussion with research and writing. If listed as WR, fulfills the post-freshman writing requirement.",
  "course_notes": "(Same as SPAN 485 1) This course examines the documentary film genre in Latin America, focusing on critical issues such as migration, social inequality, human rights struggles, the reconstruction of testimonies, historical memory, the displacement and exploitation of indigenous populations, as well as political and military repression. With the rise of new technologies for creating documentaries, we will explore the meaning of documenting Latin America in the global era through international, local, and independent productions. In addition, the course will explore how Latin America is represented through the increasing presence of documentaries on digital platforms and websites. Students will engage with these trends through oral presentations and develop their own documentation projects on Latin America. PREREQUISITES: At least one Foundational Course (SPAN 300 - 318W), or one 400-level Spanish course, or permission from the instructor.",
